	In this Part, except where otherwise provided, “week” means a period ofseven days beginning with Sunday or such other period as may be prescribed inrelation to any particular case or class of cases.
	For the purposes of this Part, a person’s normal weekly earnings are,subject to subsection (8), to be taken to be the average weekly earnings whichin the relevant period have been paid to the person or paid for the person’sbenefit under the contract of service with the employer in question.
	For the purposes of subsection (6) “earnings” and “relevant period” havethe meanings given to them by regulations.
	In such cases as may be prescribed, a person’s normal weekly earnings areto be calculated in accordance with regulations.
	Where— 
		in consequence of the establishment of one or more National Health Servicetrusts under the National Health Service Act 2006, the National Health Service(Wales) Act 2006 or the National Health Service (Scotland) Act 1978, aperson’s contract of employment is treated by a scheme under any of those Actsas divided so as to constitute two or more contracts, or
		an order under paragraph 26(1) of Schedule 3 to the National Health ServiceAct 2006 provides that a person’s contract of employment is so divided,
			regulations may make provision enabling the person to elect for all of thosecontracts to be treated as one contract for the purposes of this Part or suchprovisions of this Part as may be prescribed.
	Regulations under subsection (9) may prescribe—
		the conditions that must be satisfied if a person is to be entitled to makesuch an election;
		the manner in which, and the time within which, such an election is to bemade;
		the persons to whom, and the manner in which, notice of such an election isto be given;
		the information which a person who makes such an election is to provide,and the persons to whom, and the time within which, the person is to provideit;
		the time for which such an election is to have effect;
		which one of the person’s employers under two or more contracts is to beregarded for the purposes of statutory shared parental pay as the person’semployer under the contract.
	The powers under subsections (9) and (10) are without prejudice to anyother power to make regulations under this Part.
	Regulations under any of subsections (4) to (10) must be made with theconcurrence of the Commissioners for Her Majesty’s Revenue and Customs.

